<ArticleLayout
  title="TV and Media Storage That Keeps Cables Reachable"
  description="Choose a TV or media unit that fits the screen, devices and walking space while keeping ventilation, cables and power connections reachable."
  category="Living Spaces"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/living-room.webp"
  imageAlt="A warm living room with a TV unit, tidy media storage and soft natural light"
>
  <p>
    A media unit is rarely used with only a television on it. The soundbar needs a clear line,
    consoles need ventilation, cables must reach power and somebody eventually has to clean the
    dust behind everything.
  </p>
  <p>
    Map those devices before choosing the furniture. Measure the screen, wall and walkway, then
    mark where doors and drawers will open. Closed storage can calm the room, but not if it traps
    heat or makes every connection difficult to reach.
  </p>
  <p>
    For the rest of the room, see the <a href="/categories/living-spaces/">Living Spaces</a>{" "}
    category and the <a href="/guides/living-room-storage-ideas-everyday-australian-homes/">living room storage guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>The Media Unit Has to Work With Everything Plugged In</h2>
  <p>
    A good TV unit should make the living room easier to use, not just hold a screen. For
    most Australian homes, the right media setup is one that fits the TV comfortably, leaves
    enough room to move, gives devices and cables a practical home, and can be cleaned
    without pulling the whole room apart.
  </p>
  <p>
    A larger or more expensive entertainment unit is not automatically better if it blocks a
    walkway, hides power points, crowds a small room or makes device access harder.
    The useful choice starts with the TV, the wall, the devices and the way the household
    actually uses the room.
  </p>

  <h2>Map the Screen, Devices and Power Points</h2>
  <p>
    Start by measuring the actual width of the TV, not just the advertised screen size.
    Screen size is measured diagonally, so a 55-inch or 65-inch TV does not tell you how wide
    the unit needs to be. Also check whether the TV sits on side feet, a central stand or a
    wall mount.
  </p>
  <p>
    The wall matters just as much as the screen. Measure the available wall width and look at
    the seating position. A TV unit might fit the TV but still feel wrong if it crowds the
    sofa area, blocks a sliding door or sits awkwardly under a window.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check existing power points, antenna points, data points and any device connections
    before choosing furniture. Also look at glare from windows, curtain movement, balcony
    doors and walkways. Product photos often show wide blank walls and large rooms; many
    Australian apartments, townhouses and open-plan homes need more careful planning.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure Width, Depth, Height and Walkway Clearance</h2>
  <p>
    Measure the unit width against both the TV and the wall. If the TV is not wall mounted,
    check whether its feet or central stand fit fully on the top surface. A unit that is wide
    enough for the screen may still be too narrow for the feet.
  </p>
  <p>
    Depth is easy to underestimate. Consoles, streaming boxes, soundbars, power boards and
    cable bends all need room. A shallow unit can look neat in a photo but become frustrating
    if devices sit half out of the shelf or cables are crushed behind it.
  </p>
  <p>
    Height affects the way the TV sits in the room. Check it against the sofa position and
    the screen placement without trying to force a universal rule. Also measure walkway
    clearance, drawer opening space and whether cupboards can open without hitting a rug,
    coffee table or nearby furniture. For sofa size and viewing-zone clearance, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/sofa-and-seating-layout-what-to-measure-before-buying-furniture/">sofa and seating layout guide</a>{" "}
    can help you measure the seating area before choosing the media setup. If a rug is part
    of the room plan, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-rug-size-and-placement-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">living room rug size guide</a>{" "}
    can help you check the furniture zone before buying.
  </p>

  <h2>TV Unit Types and Where They Work Best</h2>
  <p>
    Low TV units can suit relaxed living rooms and larger screens, but they may offer less
    hidden capacity. Long media consoles can visually balance a wide wall, though they can
    crowd apartments or smaller lounge rooms if they run too far into the walkway.
  </p>
  <p>
    Compact TV stands suit smaller rooms or secondary media areas, but they may not hold
    many devices. Corner units can work in awkward rooms, especially where windows, doors or
    power points limit wall space, but they may reduce future layout flexibility.
  </p>
  <p>
    Floating units and wall-mounted setups can look light, but they bring rental, wall
    fixing and installation considerations. Renters should avoid drilling or permanent
    changes unless approved. Use qualified help where wall fixing, mounting or electrical
    work is required.
  </p>

  <h2>Open Shelves, Drawers, Cupboards and Cable Holes</h2>
  <p>
    Open shelves make devices easy to see and reach. They can work well for consoles,
    streaming boxes and media players that need regular access. The trade-off is visible
    clutter. Cables, controllers and small accessories can make open shelves look busy.
  </p>
  <p>
    Drawers hide remotes, batteries, game controllers, manuals and spare cables, but they can
    become junk drawers without a simple system. Cupboards reduce visual clutter, but they
    may make devices harder to reach or operate if access is tight.
  </p>
  <p>
    Cable holes are useful only when they line up with the devices and power points. Check
    whether shelves are adjustable and whether closed compartments still allow practical
    access. Avoid filling every shelf just because space exists.
  </p>

  <h2>Soundbars, Consoles, Streaming Devices and Remotes</h2>
  <p>
    Soundbars need width, depth and clear placement. Check whether a soundbar will block the
    screen, TV sensor or remote signal. Some soundbars are wider or taller than expected, so
    measure the unit top and the space below the screen.
  </p>
  <p>
    Gaming consoles, streaming devices, routers, charging docks, speakers and older disc
    players all need a defined place. Some devices are deeper than they look, especially once
    cables are connected. Follow manufacturer instructions for device placement and clearance.
  </p>
  <p>
    Families and shared homes may need a clear remote and controller spot. A small drawer,
    tray or labelled basket can stop remotes, batteries, HDMI cables and game controllers
    spreading across the sofa, coffee table and floor. For broader reset points around toys,
    blankets and pet items, see the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/toy-blanket-and-everyday-clutter-control-for-living-rooms/">living-room clutter control guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Cable Access, Power Points and Everyday Use</h2>
  <p>
    Check the power point location before choosing a unit. If the unit blocks the power point
    completely, everyday use and cleaning become harder. Think about antenna, HDMI, Ethernet,
    charging, speaker and device cables before deciding where the unit will sit. If lamps or
    glare are part of the media-area problem, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-lighting-ideas-for-australian-homes/">living room lighting guide</a>{" "}
    can help with power point and screen-reflection checks.
  </p>
  <p>
    Cable boxes, clips, sleeves and ties can help, but they do not replace the need for
    access. A tidy cable setup should still be practical to update when a console, streaming
    box or router changes. Keep cords away from walkways and avoid overloading power boards.
    The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-cable-management-what-to-plan-before-buying-organisers/">living-room cable management guide</a>{" "}
    covers device mapping, power-board access and cleaning around cords in more detail.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep power boards and plugs accessible enough to check and clean. Do not plan in-wall
    cable routing, new power points or wall-mounted devices without qualified help where
    required. For broader clutter planning, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-storage-ideas-everyday-australian-homes/">living room storage guide</a>{" "}
    covers remotes, chargers and everyday reset zones.
  </p>

  <h2>Small Living Rooms, Apartments and Rentals</h2>
  <p>
    Small living rooms may need lower, narrower or more visually quiet units. A media console
    that looks balanced in a large showroom may overwhelm an apartment lounge or a compact
    open-plan space. Check the walkway between the sofa, coffee table, TV unit and balcony
    door before buying. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/side-tables-coffee-tables-and-console-tables-what-to-compare-before-you-buy/">living-room tables guide</a>{" "}
    can help you compare coffee table and side table clearance alongside the media area.
  </p>
  <p>
    Apartments can have limited walls, awkward power points, sliding doors or fixed air
    vents. A long unit may stretch a wall nicely, but it may also block curtains, windows or
    access to a balcony. Corner units can solve one problem while making future furniture
    changes harder.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renters should be cautious with wall-mounted furniture, floating media units and anything
    that needs drilling or permanent fixing. Freestanding units are often simpler to move,
    but product dimensions, weight limits and manufacturer guidance still matter.
  </p>

  <h2>Families, Kids' Rooms and Shared Living Areas</h2>
  <p>
    Family living rooms often need more than a place for the TV. Controllers, remote
    controls, board games, books, blankets, toys and pet items can all gather around the
    media area. The TV unit may need to support the room's real use rather than only the
    screen.
  </p>
  <p>
    Closed drawers and cupboards can reduce visible clutter if they are easy to use. Open
    shelves may be better for devices used every day. In kids' rooms or shared living areas,
    think about access to cables, drawers and devices without making the layout complicated.
  </p>
  <p>
    Follow manufacturer guidance for securing furniture where relevant. Do not treat any
    unit, bracket, cabinet or organiser as a complete solution on its own. The practical aim
    is a setup that stays manageable for the household.
  </p>

  <h2>Materials, Cleaning and Everyday Wear</h2>
  <p>
    Timber-look, laminate, solid timber, metal, glass, rattan, painted finishes and fabric
    inserts all wear differently. Dark finishes can show dust. Glossy surfaces can show
    fingerprints. Glass can look lighter in a small room, but it shows marks and may be
    noisier when remotes or controllers are put down.
  </p>
  <p>
    Open shelving collects dust, especially around electronics and cables. Slatted or
    textured doors can look warm but may be harder to clean. Low units can gather dust
    underneath, and cable clutter can make vacuuming or mopping more frustrating.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check care instructions and think about whether the unit can be moved or cleaned around.
    A media cabinet that looks polished but traps cords and dust behind it may become
    annoying in everyday use.
  </p>

  <h2>Where Closed Storage Creates Heat or Access Problems</h2>
  <p>
    Open shelves give easy access but show clutter. Closed cupboards hide items but can make
    device access harder. Long media consoles can balance a wide wall but may crowd a small
    living room. Low units can look calm but may offer less hidden capacity.
  </p>
  <p>
    Wall-mounted setups can look light, but they involve rental and installation limits.
    Corner units can solve awkward wall layouts but may restrict future furniture changes.
    Glass surfaces can make a room feel lighter but need more frequent cleaning.
  </p>
  <p>
    Large drawers can hide remotes and controllers, but they can also become catch-all
    drawers. Cable concealment looks neat, but easy access matters when devices change.
    Matching furniture can look tidy, but room fit and device access should come first.
  </p>

  <h2>Test Doors, Cables and Walkways Together</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Measure the actual TV width.</li>
    <li>Check whether the TV uses side feet, a central stand or wall mounting.</li>
    <li>Measure available wall width.</li>
    <li>Measure the depth needed for devices and cables.</li>
    <li>Check power point and antenna or data point locations.</li>
    <li>Check soundbar width and height.</li>
    <li>List all devices that need to sit in or on the unit.</li>
    <li>Check drawer, cupboard and shelf access.</li>
    <li>Check walkway clearance.</li>
    <li>Check whether the unit blocks curtains, doors, vents or balcony access.</li>
    <li>Check product weight limits and manufacturer instructions.</li>
    <li>Avoid overloading shelves, drawers or power boards.</li>
    <li>Keep cords tidy and away from walkways.</li>
    <li>Keep liquids away from electrical items.</li>
    <li>Seek qualified help where electrical work, wall mounting or installation is required.</li>
    <li>Avoid permanent changes in rentals unless approved.</li>
    <li>Do not buy based only on a styled product photo.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Media Units That Create Daily Friction</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Buying based only on TV screen size.</li>
    <li>Forgetting the TV's actual width and feet position.</li>
    <li>Choosing a unit too shallow for consoles or soundbars.</li>
    <li>Blocking power points.</li>
    <li>Buying closed cabinets without thinking about device access.</li>
    <li>Leaving no room for cables.</li>
    <li>Buying a unit too large for a small living room.</li>
    <li>Forgetting drawer-opening clearance.</li>
    <li>Choosing open shelves when the household dislikes visible clutter.</li>
    <li>Treating the TV unit as general household overflow.</li>
    <li>Ignoring cleaning access.</li>
    <li>Assuming wall-mounted furniture or TVs are rental-friendly without approval.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Match the Unit to the Devices and Room</h2>
  <p>
    For small living rooms, a lower, narrower media unit may be worth considering if it
    leaves enough walkway clearance. For renters, freestanding TV units are often simpler
    than wall-mounted options, but dimensions and stability still matter.
  </p>
  <p>
    For gaming setups, open access, device depth and controller organisation may matter more
    than decorative doors. For closed cupboards, drawers and doors can reduce visible clutter
    if they still allow practical device access. For soundbars, unit width, surface depth and
    screen clearance should be checked together.
  </p>
  <p>
    For family living rooms, remote, controller and accessory zones can make the unit easier
    to maintain. For cable control, cable holes, rear access and power point location matter
    more than the number of shelves. For apartments and open-plan homes, compact dimensions
    and room flow should be checked before choosing a long media console.
  </p>

  <h2>Leave the Cables Reachable</h2>
  <p>
    A TV unit should be chosen around the room, the devices and everyday use. The strongest
    setup is usually one that fits the TV properly, leaves room to move, gives cables and
    remotes a sensible place, and can be cleaned and updated as devices change.
  </p>
  <p>
    A simple, well-measured media unit will usually work better than a large entertainment
    unit chosen mainly because it looked good online. Measure the TV, wall, devices and
    access points first, then choose the unit that leaves the room calmer, not more crowded.
  </p>

